[[File:Anders Anton von StiernmanSP186.jpg|thumb|Anders Anton von Stiernman. Engraving (1753).]] '''Anders Anton von Stiernman''' (September 27, 1695&nbsp;– March 2, 1765), was a Swedish historian and manuscript collector.
==Biography== He was born on September 27, 1695 in [[Stockholm]]. He adopted the name Stiernman after his stepfather. In 1715 he became a student in Uppsala, he hesitated in choosing between the ministry and the military, but finally came to devote himself to historical studies, which he had interest in the course of his employment as a tutor of [[Gustaf Rålamb]], whose libraries and collections at his disposal. In 1718 he was a clerk of Antiquities Archives, but was later transferred to the [[Swedish National Archives]].
He made research trips in 1722 to Copenhagen and in 1724 the Baltic provinces. In 1732 he was promoted to actuary and 1740 to secretary to the director. In 1743 he was ennobled as "von Stiernman". In 1745 he was made a member of the [[Swedish Academy of Sciences]] and in 1747 became the Secretary.
<!--In 1750 he was inserted in the "abbreviation Commission, which was assigned to investigate, how unnecessary extensively in writing within the administration could be avoided. After his ennobling, he withal frequently in parliamentary work as a member of chivalry and nobility, and was elected several times in different riksdagsdeputationer. He soon became widely known in the scholarly world, both within and outside the country as a writer and editor of many scholarly works. Among Stiernmans works marked the beginning several charter Publications: All-day nationwide and Möten besluth (Parts 1-3, 1728-33, Appendix 1743) covering the period 1521-1731, reports utaf kong the statutes, letters and decrees concerning religion (1744) for the period 1563-1735, reports utaf Royal. letters, statutes and regulations, etc. regarding the Swedish kingdom commerce, politie and œconomie (Part 1-6, 1747-75, the two last sections published posthumously), for the period 1523-1718. Another group of Stiernmans works consists of his bibliographic and biographical works: Aboa bit rata (1719), containing list of publications, in kind provided at the Royal Academy of Turku , overview of its history, and the list of professors, etc., Anonymorum Centuria prima ex scriptoribus gentis sviogothicæ (1724) and its continuation Centuria Secunda anonymorum nec non decas prima pseudonymorum (1726, continuation of handwriting), Bibliotheca suiogothica (Part 2, the period 1600-32, printed 1731, Parts 1 and 3-7 is in the handwriting), Svea and Göta höfdingaminne (part 1, 1745, reprinted 1836, Part 2, released in 1835 by Bror Emil Hildebrand ), Student registration over the Swedish realm chivalry and nobility (Part 1-2, 1754-55), Swedish landtmarskalkars story (printed in "The Swedish Library" 1759 -62). He published also by other authors works, equipped with bibliographical, historical and genealogical notes most important are: "King John III: es Chronik" of Aegidius Girs (1745), "King Sigismund and King Charles the IX des histories" of Jonas Werving (Part 1-2, 1746-47) and "King Eric XIV: des history" by Erik Jöransson Brick (1751). In the fall of 1758 worked Stiernman as President of the Academy of Sciences and held at the Bureau for abandoning a Speech on the learned sciences permission of the Svea kingdom over the moor property and påfvedömstiden (printed 1759), the first detailed petition in Swedish of Sweden's medieval literary history. Early on, he had behaved like vitterhetsidkare, including one Fröjdetal in Latin verse in Frederick I's coronation. The manuscript left Stiernman, except unprinted parts of the aforementioned works, including major collections relating to the nobility under the title Suecia Illustris (genealogical tables, biographical information, etc., 27 bands in folio). --> He died on March 2, 1765.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |author= |coauthors= |editor= |encyclopedia=[[Nordisk familjebok]] |title=Anders Anton von Stiernman |url=http://runeberg.org/nfcf/0719.html |isbn= |pages= |quote= | accessdate=2011-01-28 }}</ref>
==Legacy== His manuscripts were acquired after his death by [[Uppsala University Library]] and through purchase and partly through the donation of his son, Olof Celsius von Stiernman.
