'''Boris Alekseevich Kuftin''' (February 2, 1892, in [[Samara, Russia]] - August 2, 1953, in Lielupe (now a part of [[Jūrmala]]) was a Soviet [[archaeologist]] and [[ethnographer]]. From 1933 to 1953, he worked in [[Tbilisi]], [[Georgian SSR]]. In the 1930s, he discovered the [[Trialeti culture]];<ref name="Moisheson2001">{{cite book|last=Moisheson|first=Boris|title=Armenoids in prehistory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9NSAAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=15 November 2012|date=May 2001|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=978-0-7618-1780-2}}</ref> and in 1940, he coined the term [[Kura–Araxes culture|Kura-Araxes]].<ref name="Potts2012">{{cite book|last=Potts|first=D. T.|title=A Companion to the Archaeology of the Ancient Near East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P5q7DDqMbF0C&pg=PA676|accessdate=15 November 2012|date=15 August 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4443-6077-6|pages=676–}}</ref> He participated in the [[South Turkmenistan Complex Archaeological Expedition]] in the 1940s-1950s.<ref name="ShawJameson2008">{{cite book|last1=Shaw|first1=Ian|last2=Jameson|first2=Robert|title=Dictionary of Archaeology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8HKDtlPuM2oC&pg=PA81|accessdate=15 November 2012|date=15 April 2008|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-75196-1|pages=81–}}</ref>
Kuftin became a member of the [[Georgian National Academy of Sciences]] in 1946.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://science.org.ge/newsite/?page_id=1919 |title=Deceased academicians|publisher=[[Georgian National Academy of Sciences]]|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref>
