[[Image:Dickey Chapelle.jpg|thumb|275px|Chapelle at the Don Phuc [[command post]] on the Vietnamese–Cambodian border, 1964.]]
'''Georgette Louise Meyer''' (March 14, 1919 &ndash; November 4, 1965) known as '''Dickey Chapelle'''<ref>"Dickey Chapelle." ''Almanac of Famous People''. Gale, 2011. ''Biography In Context''. Web. 27 Feb. 2013.</ref> was an American [[photojournalist]] known for her work as a [[war correspondent]] from [[World War II]] through the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/topics/chapelle</ref>
==Early life== Chapelle was born in [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]] and attended [[Shorewood High School (Wisconsin)|Shorewood High School]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Shorewood School District to honor alumni, ex-teachers |publisher=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]] |date=2003-05-07 |url=http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=138868 |accessdate=2007-09-17 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> By the age of sixteen, she was attending [[aeronautics|aeronautical design]] classes at [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]]. She soon returned home, where she worked at a local airfield, hoping to learn to pilot airplanes instead of designing them. However, when her mother learned that she was also having an affair with one of the pilots, Chapelle was forced to live with her grandparents in Coral Gables, [[Florida]]. There, she wrote press releases for an air show, which led to an assignment in Havana, Cuba.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Dickey Chapelle Under Fire: Photographs by the First American Female War Correspondent Killed in Action|last=Garofolo|first=John|publisher=Wisconsin Historical Society Press|year=2015|isbn=9780870207181|location=Madison, Wisconsin|pages=2}}</ref>
A story on a Cuban air show disaster that Chapelle submitted to the ''New York Times'' got her noticed by an editor at Transcontinental and Western Air (TWA), which prompted her to move to [[New York City]]. Working at the TWA publicity bureau, she began to take weekly photography classes with Tony Chapelle, who became her husband in October 1940. She eventually quit her job at TWA to compile a portfolio, which she sold to ''Look'' magazine in 1941.<ref name=":0" /> Later, after fifteen years of marriage, divorced Tony, and changed her first name to Dickey.
==Breakthrough== Despite her mediocre photographic credentials, during [[World War II]] Chapelle managed to become a [[war correspondent]] photojournalist for [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]], and with one of her first assignments, was posted with the [[United States Marine Corps|Marines]] during the [[battle of Iwo Jima]]. She covered the [[battle of Okinawa]] as well.
After the war, she traveled all around the world, often going to extraordinary lengths to cover a story in any war zone. During the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956]], Chapelle was captured and jailed for over seven weeks. She later learned to jump with [[paratrooper]]s, and usually travelled with troops. This led to frequent awards, and earned the respect of both the military and journalistic community. Chapelle "was a tiny woman known for her refusal to kowtow to authority and her signature uniform: [[Battledress|fatigues]], an Australian [[Slouch hat|bush hat]], dramatic [[Harlequin]] glasses, and pearl earrings."<ref name="biography">{{cite book|title=Fire in the Wind: The Biography of Dickey Chapelle|last=Ostroff|first=Roberta|date=February 11, 1992|publisher=Ballantine Books|year=|isbn=0-345-36274-8|location=|page=|pages=}}</ref> [[Image:Huet, Chapelle.jpg|thumb|170px|[[Henri Huet]]'s photograph of Chapelle receiving the [[last rites]] in Vietnam.]]
==Later life== Despite early support for [[Fidel Castro]],<ref>{{cite journal | last = Chapelle | first = Dickey | title = What's A Woman Doing Here?: A Reporter's Report on Herself | pages =254–278 | publisher = William Morrow and Company | location = New York | year = 1962 | url = http://www.latinamericanstudies.org/cuban-rebels/chapelle.htm | accessdate =13 March 2018}}</ref> Chapelle was an outspoken anti-[[Communist]], and loudly expressed these views at the beginning of the [[Vietnam War]]. Her stories in the early 1960s extolled the American [[military advisor]]s who were already fighting and dying in [[South Vietnam]], and the Sea Swallows, the anticommunist militia led by Father [[Nguyen Lac Hoa]]. Chapelle was killed in Vietnam on November 4, 1965 while on patrol with a Marine platoon during Operation Black Ferret, a search and destroy operation 16&nbsp;km south of [[Chu Lai]], [[Quang Ngai Province]], [[I Corps (South Vietnam)|I Corps]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Johnson |first=Charles |title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: The Landing and the Buildup, 1965 (Marine Corps Vietnam Operational Historical Series) |publisher=Marine Corps Association |year=1978 |isbn=978-0-89839-259-3 |pages=93–96}}</ref> The lieutenant in front of her kicked a tripwire [[boobytrap]], consisting of a [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] shell with a [[hand grenade]] attached to the top of it. Chapelle was hit in the neck by a piece of shrapnel which severed her carotid artery, and she died soon afterwards. Her last moments were captured in a photograph by [[Henri Huet]].<ref name="biography"/> Her body was repatriated with an [[honor guard]] consisting of six Marines, and she was given full Marine burial. She became the first female war correspondent to be killed in Vietnam, as well as the first American female reporter to be [[killed in action]].<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=mlQJrG0EASAC&pg=PA67 |title= Brown Water, Black Berets: Coastal and Riverine Warfare in Vietnam |first= Thomas |last= Cutler |authorlink=Thomas J. Cutler |publisher= Naval Institute Press |year= 2012 |page= 67 |ISBN= 978-1-61251-184-9 |quote=Dickey Chapelle, the first American woman war correspondent ever to die in action.}}</ref>
==Awards== *[[Overseas Press Club]]'s George Polk Award for best reporting in any medium, requiring exceptional courage and enterprise abroad.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} *[[National Press Photographers Association]] 1963 "Photograph of the Year" award for her photograph of a combat-ready Marine in Vietnam.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} *Distinguished Service Award, presented by the U.S. Marine Corps Combat Correspondents Association.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}
==Legacy== *The [[Marine Corps League]], in conjunction with the [[United States Marine Corps]], honors her memory by presenting the [[Dickey Chapelle Award]] annually to recognize the woman who has contributed most to the morale, welfare and well being of the men and women of the United States Marine Corps.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcleague.com/mdp/index.php?module=ContentExpress&func=display&ceid=3 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050103085453/http://www.mcleague.com/mdp/index.php?module=ContentExpress&func=display&ceid=3 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2005-01-03 |title=Marine Corps League National Awards |accessdate= |website=Marine Corps League |publisher= |last= |first= |df= }}</ref> *In 1966, a memorial was put near the site of her death, with a plaque with the message: "She was one of us and we will miss her."<ref name="usnews1">https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/wisconsin/articles/2017-09-18/photographer-who-died-in-vietnam-named-honorary-marine</ref> *Chapelle is one of the women featured in the [[documentary film]] ''No Job for a Woman: The Women Who Fought to Report WWII'' (2011).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nojobforawoman.com/reporters/dickey-chapelle/ |title=Dickey Chapelle - Women War Reporters |website=No Job for a Woman}}</ref> *The Milwaukee Press Club inducted Chapelle into their Hall of Fame in October 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://milwaukeepressclub.org/events/milwaukee-media-hall-of-fame-2014-2/|title=Milwaukee Media Hall of Fame 2014 - Milwaukee Press Club|website=milwaukeepressclub.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cjr.org/united_states_project/dickey_chapelle_female_correspondent_killed_in_combat.php|title=Remembering ‘fearless’ war photographer Dickey Chapelle|work=Columbia Journalism Review|access-date=2018-03-25|language=en}}</ref> *In 2015, Milwaukee PBS produced a documentary about her titled ''Behind the Pearl Earrings: The Story of Dickey Chapelle, Combat Photojournalist.''<ref name="usnews1"/> *The Marine Corps Combat Correspondents Association posthumously awarded her The Brigadier General Robert L. Denig Sr. Memorial Distinguished Service Award (DSA) in August 2015.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} *In 2017, Chapelle was declared an honorary Marine at the Marine Corps Combat Correspondents Association's annual dinner.<ref name="usnews1"/>
==Publications== *{{cite book | last = Chapelle | first = Dickey | title = Needed - Women in Government Service | publisher = R. M. McBride | year = 1942 }} *{{cite book | last = Chapelle | first = Dickey | title = Girls at Work in Aviation | publisher = Doubleday, Doran | year = 1943 }} *{{cite book | last = Chapelle | first = Dickey | title = How Planes Get There | publisher = Harper | year = 1944 | series = Young America's aviation library }} *{{cite book | last = Chapelle | first = Dickey | title = What's a Woman Doing Here?: A Reporter's Report on Herself | publisher = Morrow | year = 1962 | series = Young America's aviation library | location = New York}} *{{cite book | last = Chapelle | first = Dickey |chapter = How Castro Won | editor-last = Osanka | editor-first = Franklin Mark | editor2-last = Eluntington | editor2-first = Samuel P | title = Modern Guerrilla WarFare: Fighting Communist Guerrilla Movements : 1941-1961 | location = New York | publisher = Free Press of Glencoe | year = 1962 | pages = 325–335 }}
