[[File:Diocletian's Palace (original appearance).jpg|thumb|right|250px|Reconstruction of the [[Diocletian's Palace|Palace of the Roman Emperor Diocletian]] in its original appearance upon completion in 305 CE, by Ernest Hébrard]] '''Ernest Hébrard''' (1875&ndash;1933) was a [[France|French]] [[architect]], [[archaeologist]] and [[urban planner]] who completed major projects in Greece, Morocco, and French Indochina. He is renowned for his urban plan for the redevelopment of the center of [[Thessaloniki]] in [[Greece]] after a great fire in 1917.
==Work in Greece== The majority of Thessaloniki was largely destroyed in the [[Great Thessaloniki Fire of 1917|Great Fire of 1917]]. The Greek Prime Minister [[Eleftherios Venizelos]] forbade the reconstruction of the city center until a modern city plan was approved. He commissioned Ernest Hébrard for the work, which the architect conceived and developed with the aid of the Greek architects Aristotelis Zachos and Konstantinos Kitsikis.<ref>{{cite web| publisher=[[Benaki Museum]]| website=neohellenic architecture archives| title=Konstantinos Biris (1899-1980)| access-date=16 March 2015| url=http://www.benaki.gr/index.asp?id=1020403&lang=en| deadurl=yes| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402142301/http://www.benaki.gr/index.asp?id=1020403&lang=en| archivedate=2 April 2015| df=}}</ref> The plan did away with the medieval and [[Orient]]al ([[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]]) features of Thessaloniki, preserved its [[Byzantine architecture|Byzantine]] heritage, and transformed it into a city with boulevards and contemporary roadways, squares and parks. Hébrard taught at the [[National Technical University of Athens]], and his work is well known in the architecture schools of Greece.
==Work in Africa and Asia== Hébrard was also involved in major projects in Africa and Asia, such as the upgrading of [[Casablanca]], the reconstruction of [[Diocletian]]'s palace at [[Split (city)|Split]], and later the planning for the main cities in [[French Indochina]]. He was appointed the head of the Indochina Architecture and Town Planning Service in 1923. He worked to incorporate into the French architecture being built there elements of vernacular design from the colonial territories of [[French Indochina]], now Việt Nam, Cambodia and Laos.<ref name="Hahn2013">{{cite book|last1=Rujivacharakul|first1=Vimalin|last2=Hahn|first2=H. Hazel|last3=Oshima|first3=Ken Tadashi|first4=Peter |last4=Christensen|title=Architecturalized Asia: Mapping a Continent through History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FCoWAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA178|date=2013|publisher=Hong Kong University Press|isbn=978-988-8208-05-0|page=178}}</ref> He designed the [[Cửa Bắc Church]] in central [[Hanoi]]. Hébrard oversaw the design of the French hill station of Dalat in Annam, Vietnam's middle province.<ref>{{cite book |last= Crossette|first= Barbara|date= 1998|title= The Great Hill Stations of Asia|url= |location= Boulder, CO|publisher= Westview Press|page= |isbn=9780813333267}}</ref> After his work in Indochina he went again to Athens and worked for the Greek state.
In 1931 he returned to Paris, where he died at the age of 58 two years later.
