'''Muhammad al-Khushanī''', or '''Al-Khushanī of Qayrawān''' ([[Kairouan]], unknown date - [[Córdoba, Spain|Córdoba]], 971), was an [[Arab]] [[historian]], [[jurist]] and [[judge]].<ref name=Safran>{{cite book|last1=Safran|first1=Janina M.|title=Defining Boundaries in al-Andalus: Muslims, Christians, and Jews in Islamic Iberia|date=2013|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=9780801468001|page=50}}</ref><ref name=mcweb>{{cite web|url=http://www.paulyonline.brill.nl/entries/christian-muslim-relations/al-khushani-COM_23370?s.num=0 |title=Al-Khushanī - Brill Reference |publisher=Paulyonline.brill.nl |date= |accessdate=2015-03-12}}</ref>

After the rise of the [[Fatimid Caliphate#Expansion|Fatamid conquest in Tunisia]], al-Khushani fled to the [[Caliph of Córdoba|Umayyad court in Cordoba]] in 923 AD, like other [[Maliki]] scholars did at the time. He is famous for his collection of documents, titled ''Kitāb al-qudā bi-Qurtuba'', where he fills documents of the [[Al-Andalus|Andalusian]] archives, [[oral tradition]] and biographical information about the [[qadi]] of [[Córdoba, Spain|Córdoba]]. He also wrote extensively on the various [[madhabs]] in his time, including the [[Hanafi]] and [[Ismaili]].<ref name=Walker>{{cite book|last1=Walker|first1=Paul E.|title=Exploring an Islamic empire : Fatimid history and its sources|date=2002|publisher=I.B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=9781860646928|pages=133–34, 155}}</ref> He died in 971 AD.

