{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}
'''Peter Bielik''' is a Slovak historian, who withdrew his candidacy for director of the [[National Memory Institute (Slovakia)|National Memory Institute]] due to controversy over his remarks blaming Jewish [[Holocaust survivors]] for the September 1945 [[Topoľčany pogrom]].

==Life==
Bielik was an editor of ''Svedectvo'' ("Testimony"), a journal published by the Political Prisoners' Association of Anti-Communist Resistance (PV ZPKO), and an official representative of the PV ZPKO.{{sfn|Nedelsky|2016|pp=973, 976}} The journal, which has been criticized by Slovakia's Jewish community, is noted for undercurrents of [[antisemitism]] and frequently publishing [[apologetic]], mythologizing articles about convicted Slovak nationalist war criminals.{{sfn|Nedelsky|2016|pp=983–986}}

Following the death of [[Ján Langoš]], the director of the [[National Memory Institute (Slovakia)|National Memory Institute]], in 2006, the rightwing [[Slovak National Party]] (SNS) proposed Bielik as a candidate for his replacement.{{sfn|Nedelsky|2016|p=976}} In an article the previous year, Bielik had criticized the documentary ''[[Miluj blížneho svojho]]'' ("Love thy neighbor"), about the [[Topoľčany pogrom]], because he felt it was [[anti-Catholic]]. Instead, Bielik cited contemporary reports stating that "the Jews behaved very arrogantly and imperiously, trying to systematically occupy important positions in the economic, public, and political spheres". In his article, Bielik made no mention of the Holocaust,{{sfn|Nedelsky|2016|pp=976–977}} which claimed the lives of the majority of Slovak Jews, and was perpetrated by the collaborationist [[Slovak State]] in concert with [[Nazi Germany]].{{sfn|Kamenec|2002|p=130}}

Bielik presents Slovaks who stole from Jews during the war as victims of the Jews' efforts to regain their property, and the Jews as ungrateful to the majority of Slovaks to whom they supposedly owed their lives. His perspective was criticized by the contemporary Slovak media, which identified him as a supporter of the Slovak State.{{sfn|Nedelsky|2016|pp=976–977}} The Slovak Jewish newspaper ''Delet'' criticized Bielik for blaming Jews for the Topoľčany pogrom and accused him of [[Holocaust trivialization|minimizing the Holocaust]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lesná |first1=Ľuba |title=Quo Vadis Matica slovenská? |url=http://www.delet.sk/spravy-a-politika/editorial/quo-vadis-matica-slovenska |accessdate=11 October 2018 |work=Delet |date=8 February 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708015429/http://www.delet.sk/spravy-a-politika/editorial/quo-vadis-matica-slovenska |archive-date=8 July 2018 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref> American historian Nadya Nedelsky compared Bielik's portrayal of the Jews with that of President [[Jozef Tiso]], a noted Holocaust perpetrator in Slovakia: to Tiso, Slovak people were victims saving themselves by deporting Jews, while to Bielik, the Slovaks are "victims and saviors of these [Jewish] perpetrators". As a result of the controversy, he withdrew his candidacy for the directorship.{{sfn|Nedelsky|2016|p=978}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Franek |first1=Jaro |title=Malé slovenské škandály |url=https://www.holocaust.cz/zdroje/clanky-z-ros-chodese/ros-chodes-2007/brezen-7/male-slovenske-skandaly-2/ |publisher=Terezín Initiative |accessdate=11 October 2018 |trans-title=A small Slovak scandal |language=cs |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170528045709/http://www.holocaust.cz/zdroje/clanky-z-ros-chodese/ros-chodes-2007/brezen-7/male-slovenske-skandaly-2/ |archive-date=28 May 2017 |dead-url=no |df= }}</ref> However, he still ran for the Board of Directors, whose nominees have to be approved by the [[Slovak Parliament]]; he was unsuccessful.{{sfn|Nedelsky|2016|pp=979–980}}

In 2008, Bielik published a book titled ''Masoneria – nieszczęście naszych czasów'' ("Freemasonry — the plague of our time"), in which he blamed [[Mason (Freemasonry)|Freemasons]] for a host of social problems, including "revolts, upheavals, revolutions, murders... heresy, secularization, atheism, spiritualism, reincarnation, radical feminism, pornography, artificial contraception, sterilization, divorce, abortion and euthanasia" according to the Polish magazine ''[[Focus.pl|Focus]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pytko |first1=Kazimierz |title=Opłaceni przez diabła |url=https://www.focus.pl/artykul/oplaceni-przez-diabla |accessdate=11 October 2018 |work=[[Focus.pl|Focus]] |date=29 December 2008 |language=pl-PL}}</ref>

{{As of|2018}}, Bielik was the chairman of the board of Camera Obskura, a non-profit organization that organized a conference on the [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia]] at [[Comenius University]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Konferencia August '68 v Bratislave privíta popredných domácich aj zahraničných historikov |url=https://www.bratislavskenoviny.sk/zivot-v-meste/51080-konferencia-august-68-v-bratislave-privita-poprednych-domacich-aj-zahranicnych-historikov |accessdate=17 November 2018 |work=Bratislavské noviny |agency=TASR |date=16 September 2018 |language=sk}}</ref>

