[[Image:Horovathos.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Photo of the Tanais Tablet B containing the word Χοροάθος (Horoáthos).]] The '''Tanais Tablets''' are two tablets dated late 2nd-3rd century AD, and written in [[Greek language|Greek]] from the city of [[Tanais]], in the proximity of modern [[Rostov-on-Don]], [[Russia]].{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=15}}<ref>{{cite book |last=Ustinova |first=Yulia |date=1999 |title=The Supreme Gods of the Bosporan Kingdom: Celestial Aphrodite and the Most High God |url=https://books.google.cl/books?id=ARyeneZne9gC&pg=PA194&dq=tanais+stone&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2mqmU5ruGIvboASd1ICYDg&ved=0CFgQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=tanais%20stone&f=false |location= |publisher=Brill |page=194 |isbn=9004112316 |accessdate=June 22, 2014}}</ref> At the time, Tanais was composed of a mixed [[Greek people|Greek]] and [[Sarmatians|Sarmatian]] population. The tablets are public inscriptions which commemorate renovation works in the city. One of the tablets, Tanais Tablet A, is damaged and is not fully reconstructed.{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=19-20}} The other one, Tanais Tablet B, is fully preserved and is dated to 220 AD.{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=22}}
The tablets were discovered by Russian archaeologist Pavel Mikhailovich Leontjev in 1853 and are today kept in the lapidary of the [[Hermitage Museum]] in [[Saint Petersburg]].{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=9}} The tablets are considered important for the early [[Croats|Croatian]] history.
==Significance== Among the names on the tablets are those of three men: Horoúathos, Horoáthos, and Horóathos (Χορούαθ[ος], Χοροάθος, Χορόαθος).{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=9}} Those names scholars interpret as [[anthroponym]]s of the Croatian ethnonym ''Hrvat''.{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=25-27}} The ethnonym ''Hrvat'' is generally considered to be of Iranian origin,<ref name="Gluhak">{{citation |first=Alemko |last=Gluhak |author-link=Alemko Gluhak |title=Podrijetlo imena Hrvat |trans-title=The origin of the ethnonym Hrvat |publisher=[[Jezik]] (Croatian Philological Society) |location=Zagreb |year=1990 |url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=116509&lang=en |language=Croatian |pages=131–133}}</ref><ref name="Matasovic">{{citation |first=Ranko |last=Matasović |author-link=Ranko Matasović |title=Poredbenopovijesna gramatika hrvatskoga jezika |trans-title=A Comparative and Historical Grammar of Croatian |publisher=[[Matica hrvatska]] |location=Zagreb |year=2008 |isbn=978-953-150-840-7 |language=Croatian |pages=44}}</ref> and that can be traced to the Tanais Tablets.<ref name="Gluhak"/>{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=25-27}} The Tanais Tablet B mentions Horoathos as the son of Sandarz which is a [[Scythian languages|Scytho-Sarmatian]] name, and scholars view this as an indication that early Croats could have been at that time [[Sarmatians]] or [[Alans]] who became [[Slavicisation|Slavicized]] in the following centuries.<ref name="Gluhak"/>{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=25-27}}
==Research history== The tablets were discovered by the Russian archeologist Pavel Mihajlovič Leontjev (1822-1874) in September 1853. Mostly international scholars wrote about the tablets, while of Croatian scholars [[Stjepan Krizin Sakač]], [[Dominik Mandić]] and [[Radoslav Katičić]].{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=10}} However, during the time of [[Yugoslavia]], Yugoslavian scholars avoided discussing them,{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=21}} or mainly wrote about them in a superficial way and misinterpreted ([[Ferdo Šišić]], [[Trpimir Macan]], Josip Horvat, [[Bogo Grafenauer]], Jaroslav Šidak, Gordan Ravančić, Ivan Biondić, Stjepan Pantelić etc.),{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=10-19}} and sometimes malicious manner, for example, [[Miroslav Krleža]] saw the connection as "historical lunacy", while [[Nada Klaić]] ignored and only mentioned them for the criticizing of the Iranian-Caucasian theory of the Croatian ethnogenesis.{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=11}} The open debate only followed after the collapse of Yugoslav Communism.{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=11}}
First who connected the tablets personal names with Croatian ethnonym was A. L. Pogodin in 1902,{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=263}}{{sfn|Heršak, Lazanin|1999|p=26}} while first who considered such a thesis and Iranian origin was [[Konstantin Josef Jireček]] in 1911.{{sfn|Košćak|1995|p=110}} It should be noted that some scholars use this tablets only to explain the etymology, and not necessarily the ethnogenesis.{{sfn|Heršak, Nikšić|2007|p=260}}
However, whether the early Croats have been Slavs who taken the name of Iranian origin or were ruled by Sarmatian elite caste,<ref name="Gluhak"/> or were Slavicized Sarmatians,<ref name="Gluhak"/> the remote Irano-Sarmatian elements or influences on the Croatian ethnogenesis cannot be entirely excluded.{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=12}}{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=21}} Still, the secure connection of those three personal names with the Croatian ethnonym, or ethnic identity, is rather difficult without more evidence.{{sfn|Džino|2010|p=21}}
==Tanais Tablet A== [[File:Танаис, археологический музей-заповедник-14.jpg|thumb|Tanais table A]]
The Tablet A is the larger and older inscription, dated to 175-211 AD, and which originates from the time when king [[Tiberius Julius Sauromates II]] (175-211 AD) ruled the [[Bosporan Kingdom]].{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=19}} The marble tablet (0.92 x 0.73 x 0.09) probably sustained heavy damage even before the excavation.{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=19}} Thirty-two lines from thirty fragments were saved from the inscription.{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=20}} The public inscription mentions the king, the synod, or devotional assembly, the leadership of the devotional assembly, and its regular members, which were slightly less than forty.{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=20}} The fourth line ends by mentioning of the father of the devotional assembly, Horoúathos (Χορούαθος), who is referred to by name in the fifth line,{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=20}} and amongst others an unknown male who is said to be the son of Horoáthos (Χοροάθου) is also cited.{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=21}} The inscription ends with the date, from which is saved only the appellation of the Greek-Macedonian month, which corresponds to either July or August.{{sfn|Škegro|2005|p=21}}
'''Greek original:''' <poem lang="grc"> ΘΕΩι ΥΨΙΣΤΩι. ΆΓΑΘΗι ΤΥΧΗι.
ΒΑΣΙΛΕΥΟΝΤΟΣ ΒΑΣΙΛΕΩΣ ΤΙΒ(ΕΡΙΟΥ) ΙΟΥΛ(ΙΟΥ) ΣΑΥΡΟΜΑΤΟΥ ΦΙΛΟΚΑΙΣΑΡ[ΟΣ ΚΑ]Ι ΦΙΛΟ[Ρ]ΩΜΑΙΟΥ, ΕΥΣΕΒΟΥΣ, Η ΣΥΝΟΔΟΣ Η ΠΕΡΙ Ι[ΕΡΕΑ ΙΟΥ)ΛΙΟΝ ΡΑΛΧΑΔΟΥ ΚΑΙ ΠΑΤΕΡΑ Σ[Υ]ΝΟΔΟΥ ΧΟΡΟΥΑΘ[ΟΝ]-----Ο — ΚΑΙ ΣΥΝΑΓΩΓΩΝ ΆΡΔΑ[ΡΑ] ΚΟΝ [Σ]ΥΝΕΓΔΗΜ[ΟΥ ΚΑΙ ΦΙΛ]ΑΓ[ΑΘ]ΟΝ ΔΙΑΙ[Ο]Ν ΚΕΡΔΩΝΑΚΟΥ (?) ΚΑΙ [Π]ΑΡΑΦΙΛΑΓΑΘΟ[Ν]------ΙΟΝ ΦΟΡΓΑΒΑΚ[ΟΥ] ΚΑΙ [ΝΕΑ]ΝΙΣ- [Κ]ΑΡΧΗΝ ΔΗΜΗΤ[ΡΙΟΝ ΑΠΟ]ΛΛΩΝΙΟΥ ΚΑΙ ΓΥΜ(Ν]ΑΣΙΑ[ΡΧΗΝ] ΒΑ - [ΣΙ]ΛΕΙΔΗΝ ΘΕΟΝ[ΕΙΚ]Ο[Υ ΚΑΙ Α]ΤΤΑΝ ΗΡΑΚΛΕΙΔΟΥ ΦΙΛΟ[Ν]? ΤΗΣ [ΣΥ]ΝΟΔΟΥ [ΚΑΙ] ΟΙ ΛΟ[ΙΠΟ]Ι [ΘΙΑ]ΣΪΤΑΙ· ΆΡΔΑΡΑΚΟΣ ΖΙΑ---ΟΥ, ΔΗ[ΜΗΤ]ΡΙΟΣ------ΟΥ, ΛΕΙΜΑΝΟΣ ΦΙΔΑ, [ΜΙ]ΔΑΧΟΣ?-------ΑΝΟΥ, Ά[ΣΚ]ΛΗΠΙΑΔΗΣ ΟΥΑΛΕ[Ρ]ΙΟΥ . .Γ?ΟΔΑΝ[Ο]Σ [ΔΗΜΗΤ?]ΡΙΟΥ, [Μ]ΕΝΕΣΤΡΑΤΟΣ ΛΥΚΙΣ [ΚΟ]Υ --------ΙΚΑΧΟ[Υ], ΔΙΟΦΑΝΤ[ΟΣ] ΔΕΙΟΥ, ΠΟΠΛ[ΙΟ]Σ '''15'''-----------ΔΑ, ΗΡΑΚΛΕΙΔ[ΗΣ] ΕΠΙΓΟΝΟΥ, ΊΑΡΔΟ---------------[Δ] ΗΜΗΤΡΙΟΥ, Α[Φ]ΡΟΔΕΙΣΙΟΣ ΧΡΥΣΕ- [ΡΩΤΟΣ, ΦΑΛ]ΔΑ[ΡΑ]ΝΟΣ ΑΠΟΛΛΩΝΙΟΥ, ΦΙΛΙΠ- [ΠΟΣ]------------ΝΟ[Υ], ΚΑΛΟΫΣ ΑΘΗΝΙΟΥ, ΚΟΦΑΡΝΟΣ --------------------------------[Τ]ΡΥΦΩΝ ΑΝΔΡΟΜ[ΕΝ]ΟΥΣ,'''20''' Ο-------------------------ΧΟΡΟΑΘΟΥ, ΘΕΟΤΕΙΜΟΣ ΨΥΧΑ- ΡΙΩΝ[ΟΣ]----------ΔΙΒΑΛΟΣ ΦΑΡ[ΝΑΚΟΥ], ΕΫΙΟΣ 'ΡΟ- ΔΩΝ[ΟΣ, ΗΡΑ]ΚΛΕΙΔΗΣ "ΑΤΤ[Α----------------'ΑΡΙΣ]- ΤΟΔ[ΗΜΟΥ, Σ]ΥΜΜΑΧΟΣ ΣΑ--------------- ΚΟΣ---------------------------- '''25''' ΦΙΛΟ------------------------------ ΟΡΑΝΣ - - - [ΖΩΡΘΪ? ]ΝΟΣ ΒΕ [ ΛΛΙΚΟΥ?]------ 'ΡΑΔΑΜ[ΕΙΣΤΟΣ?)------ΦΑΔΙΝΑ[ΜΟΥ]------ ΜΥΡ[ΩΝ? ]----------ΜΑΣΤΟΫ------------ ΠΟ------------ΟΣ ΆΡΔΑ[ΡΑΚΟΥ?]------ '''50''' ΦΙΔ[Α]----------ΝΟΣ ΧΑΡΙ[ΤΩΝ--------:Α]- ΡΑΘΙ-------------------------- ΈΝ Τ[Ωι-----ΕΤΕΙ ΚΑΙ ΜΗ]ΝΙ ΛΩ[Ωι]----- </poem>
